I find the article interesting especially given the conversations I have had with American Express customer service this morning.  After being transferred, at my request, to three different supervisors, I asked the person for the name of the CEO.  Their response:  I do not know who is the CEO.  We are a global organization, mam, I cannot possibly know everyone.  I asked for them to give me the name and contact information for someone in the US that could possibly have authority to make decisions versus reading off a page.  Their response was the same.  I asked them if they knew their corporate values.  They did not.  So I read the values from the website to her.  I’m told the call was being recorded. It occurred at 7:25 a.m. CST with Simone. (and if anyone from American Express would like to contact me I am open to a conversation).  I will write a letter to the CEO as I am curious to hear how he would want his people to represent American Express given that one of his tidbits is being successful means be willing to take a bit of a risk.







Ann
Sep 13, 2013 at 11:58 pm 
I enjoyed the interview and I think Mr. Chenault’s advice and comments are valuable.  However, whether the customer service of Amex actually follows his lead is not certain.  I definitely agree the customer shoukd be a major focus (and many companies fail to realize this).  Not infrequently the CEO’s ideas get lost along the way and those at the customer service level fail to provide the service necessary to keep customers happy.  One bad exchange with customer service can send a customer to the competition — never to return.
   That is a risk some of his employees may not be recognizing.







Stephanie E Whitfield
Mar 10, 2015 at 5:30 pm 
Mr Ken Chenault craeted the american express serve for people like me who doesn’t have a real bank account. But i will be taking the CEO AMERICAN EXPRESS SERVE to court for a suit of not allowing customers to pay there bills, for online bill pay and he will loose this company. I am very serious, i will go to every news station stating how bad of a company this is for government and federal employees to use as regular normal people has used this card.







Diego
Mar 03, 2016 at 3:58 pm 
What??









Pat
Feb 28, 2016 at 4:03 pm 
I’ve met Ken on multiple occasions, extremely bright and personable guy. Has a great vision for the company and is ready to roll up his sleeves and get down to business if he needs to. 
Unfortunately, that’s where the leadership ends. I spent many years working with and For Amex and the corporate politics inside that place are at best, just as bad as any other bank and in many cases much worse.
Lots of VPs with no idea how to manage, SVPs simply pushing a balanced scorecard agenda and Directors who are faced with Gerstner’s old stack ranking methodology to enable favoritism in many cases. The review process internally isn’t transparent at all, and that’s not just a metaphor. When they review employees under director level, they do it in a conference room and literally black out the windows with paper! The output of reviews are “here’s your rating, do you accept it?” If you don’t, well, too bad. No explanation of why you received the rating you did and there’s no transparency as to who finished first and last.  
There’s no clear goals for advancement, no training for upward movement, and no clear path for most technical employees. 
So while Chenault and his team of merry makers try and figure out how to cut a billion dollars in operating costs(going to probably cut 15-25% of his workforce) over two years, it’s business as usual for those who are really doing the work. 
Good luck Ken, you’ll need it.







Jasemin Sibo
Jul 23, 2016 at 6:20 pm 
I was privileged to work with American Express in Sydney, Singapore and Kuala Lumpur offices. Amex is one of the most humane company I have ever come across, and the calibre of the leadership team is beyond exemplary. As CEO of my own startup I am applying the Blue Box values and leadership traits which I have internalized. I will always be a supporter and brand ambassador for Amex.






